  "text": "In the absence of PMA ( Figure 2E ), 1.5 µM [Ca 2ϩ ] i increased the rate of fusion pore expansion to 47 Ϯ 8 nS/s (n ϭ 264, 21 cells). This is an almost 2-fold increase compared with the rate at low [Ca 2ϩ ] i , in excellent agreement with a previous report [CITATION_1] . The pore expansion rate can thus be accelerated either by PMA or by elevated [Ca 2ϩ ] i . Measurements of [Ca 2ϩ ] i using the fluorescent indicator Fura-2 (200 µM; as in [CITATION_2] showed that with 7 mM EGTA in the pipette, [Ca 2ϩ ] i stayed constantly below 10 nM during degranulation stimulated by 20 µM GTPγS, with or without 100 nM PMA (data not shown). Thus, both GTPγS-induced fusion and the acceleration of pore expansion by PMA are not due to an elevation of [Ca 2ϩ ] i . We used staurosporine in the absence of PMA to test whether the increase in pore expansion rate at high [Ca 2ϩ ] i was mediated by calcium-dependent activation of PKC. When 2 µM staurosporine was included in the pipette solution, the pore expansion rate at 1.5 µM [Ca 2ϩ ] i was not affected ( Figure 2F ; 42 Ϯ 4 nS/s, n ϭ 292, 16 cells). Staurosporine also had no effect on the pore expansion rate at low [Ca 2ϩ ] i ( Figure 2G , 27 Ϯ 2 nS/s, n ϭ 231, 15 cells).",
